<doc id="169041" wikidata="Q5161535" url="?curid=169041" title="Connecticut General Life Insurance Co. v. Johnson">
<text>Connecticut General Life Insurance Company v. Johnson, 303 U.S. 77 (1938), is a case in which the Supreme Court of the United States dealt with corporate entities. The case involved whether California could levy a tax on a company licensed to do business in that state for transactions that occurred in a different state.

==Judgment==
Justice Stone delivered the opinion of the Court. Justice Hugo Black dissented.

